  "sourceNotes": "Gingerbread in various forms appears throughout British baking literature from the seventeenth century. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136, gives a gingerbread recipe using treacle and spice; the rolled-and-cut method became standard in the nineteenth century as refined sugar and consistent spice imports made the method accessible. Florence White, Good Things in England (1932), documents regional variations built on the same flour-butter-syrup-spice base.",
