            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Make the dough"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sift the flour, bicarbonate of soda, ginger, cinnamon, mixed spice, and salt into a large bowl. Rub in the cold butter until the mixture resembles fine breadcrumbs. Add the brown sugar and mix through. Stir in the golden syrup and beaten egg and mix to a soft dough. If the dough is sticky, add flour a tablespoon at a time. Bring together, flatten into a disc, wrap, and refrigerate for at least 30 minutes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Roll, cut, and bake"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Heat the oven to 170°C fan. Line two baking trays with baking paper. On a lightly floured surface, roll the chilled dough to about 4 mm thick. Cut into shapes with biscuit cutters and transfer to the trays with a palette knife, spacing them 3 cm apart. Re-roll the trimmings and cut again. Bake for 10 to 12 minutes, until the biscuits are firm and a shade darker at the edges. They will still feel slightly soft when hot; they firm up completely as they cool. Transfer to a rack and leave until cold before storing."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
